Question: Find the string with the maximum number of vowels.

Input:
List<String> words = Arrays.asList("hello", "world", "aeiou");

Solutions:-

Java 8 Streams find max-vowel string using max() with custom Comparator counting vowels. For input ["hello", "world", "aeiou"], returns "aeiou" (5 vowels).

#Step-by-Step Logic
Stream words â†’ max(Comparator.comparingInt(this::vowelCount)) where vowelCount returns vowel tally.

#Complete Implementation

import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Comparator;

public class MaxVowelsString {
    
    private static int vowelCount(String s) {
        return (int) s.chars()
                      .filter(ch -> "aeiouAEIOU".indexOf(ch) != -1)
                      .count();
    }
    
    public static void findMaxVowels(List<String> words) {
        words.stream()
             .max(Comparator.comparingInt(MaxVowelsString::vowelCount))
             .ifPresent(System.out::println);
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        List<String> words = Arrays.asList("hello", "world", "aeiou");
        findMaxVowels(words);  // aeiou
    }
}

#Thought Process
vowelCount uses chars().filter().count() for O(n) per string. comparingInt(vowelCount) creates length-then-lexicographic comparator. max() returns Optional. Ties pick first by stable sort.

#Edge Cases Analysis
Empty list: Empty Optional, nothing prints.
No vowels: Longest non-vowel string (0 vowels).
All same vowels: First by encounter order.
Null list: NPE on stream().
Null strings: NPE in chars(); filter first.
Empty strings: 0 vowels, shortest.
